# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: camera-monitor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] In the film and graphics industries, **3D lookup tables** (**3D LUT**s) are used for color grading and for mapping one color space to another.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] They are commonly used to calculate preview colors for a monitor or digital projector of how an image will be reproduced on another display device, typically the final digitally projected image or release print of a movie.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] A 3D LUT is a 3D lattice of output RGB color values that can be indexed by sets of input RGB colour values.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] Each axis of the lattice represents one of the three input color components; the input color thus defines a point inside the lattice.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] Since the point may not be on a lattice point, the lattice values must be interpolated; most products use trilinear interpolation.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] 3D LUTs are used extensively in the movie production chain, as part of the digital intermediate process.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] Cubes may be of various sizes and bit depths.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] Often 33×33×33 cubes are used as 3D LUTs.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] The most common practice is to use RGB 10-bit/component log images as the input to the 3D LUT.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] Output is usually RGB values that are to be placed unchanged into a display device's buffer.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] Modern GPU of graphics cards have direct support for 3D LUTs, allowing entire HD images to be processed at 60 fps or faster.
[src:camera-monitor/3d-lookup-table] Also, modern display controller of monitors have support for 3D LUTs.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:camera-monitor/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes is a line of intermediate codecs, which means they are intended for use during video editing, and not for practical end-user viewing.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] This is achieved by only using intra-frame compression, where each frame is stored independently and can be decoded with no dependencies on other frames.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] The benefit of an intermediate codec is that it offers excellent random access performance in post-production applications, and retains higher quality than end-user codecs while still requiring much less expensive disk systems compared to uncompressed video.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] It is comparable to Avid's DNxHD codec or CineForm which offer similar bitrates and are also intended to be used as intermediate codecs.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes is a DCT scalar based intra-frame-only codec and is therefore simpler to decode than distribution-oriented formats like H.264.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2018 Apple added a new "ProRes RAW" (compressed Bayer filter) to Final Cut Pro X, after Blackmagic Design implemented compressed Bayer as "CinemaDNG 3:1" and "CinemaDNG 4:1" in their cameras and DaVinci Resolve.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes supports different data rates and different resolutions.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] All ProRes422-variants use chroma subsampling of 4:2:2 at 10-bit color depth.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 and 4444 XQ samples color in the 4:4:4 schema with a color depth of 10 or 12 bits, and can optionally include an alpha channel.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 was introduced with Final Cut Studio (2009) as another in the company's line of intermediate codecs for editing material but not for final delivery.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] It shares many features with other, 422, codecs of Apple's ProRes family but provides better quality than 422 HQ in color detail.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] It has a target data rate of approximately 330 Mbit/s for 4:4:4 sources at 1920x1080 and 29.97 fps.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 XQ was introduced with Final Cut Pro X version 10.1.2 in June 2014.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] It has a target data rate of approximately 500 Mbit/s for 4:4:4 sources at 1920x1080 and 29.97 fps, and requires OS X v10.8 (Mountain Lion) or later.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In April 2018 Apple released ProRes RAW.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] It is built upon the same technology as other ProRes codecs, but is directly applied to the raw data coming from the sensor, thus delaying the debayering process to the post-production stage.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes RAW therefore aims at quality and better color reproduction, rather than performance.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] Apple ProRes RAW is available in LUMIX cameras, Nikon cameras (Z9, Z8, Z6iii), Sony Alpha FX3 via Atomos Ninja V, and as of September 2025, in the Apple iPhone 17 Pro and ProMax.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes RAW is a 16 bit uncompressed video format in .mov.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In the Sony FX3 and the Atomos Ninja V, ProRes Raw records in 16 bit and compresses in 12 bit for color data.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes RAW codec is natively available in Adobe Premiere Pro, Adobe After Effects, Assimilate Scratch, Apple Final Cut Pro and Davinci Resolve.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On 28 August 2008, Apple introduced a free ProRes QuickTime Decoder for both Mac and Windows that allows playback of ProRes files through QuickTime.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On 15 September 2011, FFmpeg introduced a free decoder for ProRes 422 for libavcodec.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] FFmbc, a fork of FFmpeg customized for broadcast and professional usage, supports ProRes 422 and 4444 files.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On 1 October 2011, JCodec introduced an open source (FreeBSD License) pure Java decoder for ProRes 422, a translation of the FFmpeg version.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] Installing Final Cut Pro will install the ProRes codecs for encoding files on macOS.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] Without Final Cut Pro installed, QuickTime Player can also be used to capture ProRes 422 video from any compatible attached camera, using the "Maximum" quality setting when producing a Movie Recording.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] Apple released ProRes bundled with other pro codecs as a download for users with "qualifying copies of Final Cut Pro, Motion, or Compressor" installed, for OS X with QuickTime 7.6 and newer.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] At the April 2010 NAB Show, Digital Video Systems launched the first Windows 7 platform with the ability to encode to all the varieties of Apple ProRes at speeds far faster than real time on their Clipster product.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On March 31, 2011, Telestream added support for ProRes encoding on Windows systems with Episode Engine, Vantage, and FlipFactory as a free upgrade to the current versions of these products.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] The system must be running on Windows Server 2008 and be able to support this feature.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes video capturing and output to tape is available in Telestream's Pipeline network encoder.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On 29 October 2011, FFmpeg introduced a free encoder, enabling ProRes 422 encoding on all FFmpeg supported platforms.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On 1 November 2011, JCodec introduced an open source (BSD License) pure Java encoder for ProRes 422.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] At the April 2012 NAB Show, Brevity introduced a customized algorithm for the accelerated transport and encoding of ProRes files.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] The Arri Alexa has a built-in ProRes recording unit for its 1080p and 2K video streams, supporting ProRes 4444 and all ProRes 422 versions.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] At NAB 2012, Blackmagic announced ProRes recording support for their HyperDeck SSD recorders as well as onboard recording on the Blackmagic Cinema Camera, and Brevity announced a GPU-based ProRes transcoder with simultaneous accelerated file transport.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2013 Blackmagic Design released the Blackmagic Cinema Camera that record in RAW and ProRes files directly in camera 4:2:2 10-bit.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2013 Convergent Design introduced their Odyssey7 and Odyssey7Q monitor/recorders that can record in Apple ProRes 422 (HQ) and are certified by Apple.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2014 Atomos introduced their latest advanced recorder Shogun that can record 4K in Apple ProRes.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2015 AJA introduced the CION production camera that can capture 4K/UltraHD/2K/HD to all Apple ProRes 422 formats as well as Apple ProRes 4444 in 12-bit.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2016 Blackmagic Design released UrsaMini 4.6k that can capture from 4.6k to HD in all Apple ProRes flavor from Proxy to 4444 in 12-bit.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2018/2019 Blackmagic Design released Pocket Cinema Camera 4K that can capture 4k/UltraHD/1080p in all Apple ProRes 422 formats.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2019 Mac Pro introduced a new "Apple Afterburner" card as an optional component to accelerate ProRes and ProRes RAW decoding.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2021, Apple announced the iPhone 13 Pro, with ProRes encoding/decoding using its built-in camera app alongside its recent addition of DNG raw photos (DNG v5.1) on the 12 Pro Models.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] ProRes encoding can be performed at up to 3840 × 2160 30p ProRes HQ with Dolby Vision HDR color profiles on models with at least 256 GB of storage, while the 128 GB model will be limited to 1080p 30p with its built-in camera application.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2023, Apple announced the iPhone 15 Pro, which added the ability to shoot ProRes in the Apple Log format, as well as the ability to shoot ProRes footage at up to 3840 x 2160 60p to an external drive via the USB-C port from the built-in camera application.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In 2021, Apple announced the Apple M1 Pro and M1 Max, variants of the Apple M1 system on a chip containing, among other new features, hardware ProRes encoding and decoding acceleration.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] In February 2022, Panasonic released the Lumix GH6 mirrorless camera which has the ability to record 5.7K video in ProRes 422 HQ.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On June 6, 2022, Apple announced the Apple M2 with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On January 17, 2023, Apple announced the Apple M2 Pro and M2 Max with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] On October 30, 2023, Apple announced the Apple M3 series of chips with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] Lasergraphics motion picture film scanning systems include support for output to ProRes 4444 HQ/XQ, ProRes 422, and others.
[src:camera-monitor/apple-prores] The ProRes codec was awarded an Engineering Emmy Award in 2020 for "Outstanding Achievement in Technology".
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] Avid was founded in August 1987 by Bill Warner, a former marketing manager from Apollo Computer.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] A prototype of their first non-linear editing system, the Avid/1 Media Composer, was shown at the National Association of Broadcasters (NAB) convention in April 1988.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] The Avid/1 was based on an Apple Macintosh II computer, with special hardware and software of Avid's design installed.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] The Avid/1 was "the biggest shake-up in editing since Melies played with time and sequences in the early 1900s".
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] By the early 1990s, Avid products began to replace such tools as the Moviola, Steenbeck, and KEM flatbed editors, allowing editors to handle their film creations with greater ease.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] The first feature film edited using the Avid was *Let's Kill All the Lawyers* in 1992, directed by Ron Senkowski.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] The film was edited at a 30fps NTSC rate, then used Avid MediaMatch to generate a negative cutlist from the EDL.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] The first feature film edited natively at 24fps with what was to become the Avid Film Composer was *Emerson Park*.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] The first studio film to be edited at 24fps was *Lost in Yonkers*, directed by Martha Coolidge.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] By 1994 only three feature films used the new digital editing system.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] By 1995 dozens had switched to Avid, and it signaled the beginning of the end of cutting celluloid.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] In 1996 Walter Murch accepted the Academy Award for editing *The English Patient* (which also won best picture), which he cut on the Avid.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] This was the first Editing Oscar awarded to a digitally edited film (although the final print was still created with traditional negative cutting).
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] In 1994 Avid introduced Open Media Framework (OMF) as an open standard file format for sharing media and related metadata.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] Over the years, Avid has released numerous freeware versions of Media Composer.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] Initially this included Avid Free DV: a free edition of Media Composer with limited functionality; Avid Xpress DV: a consumer edition of Media Composer; and then Avid Xpress Pro: a prosumer edition of Media Composer.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] These editions were discontinued in 2008 as the flagship Media Composer was lowered in price.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] Later, Avid released Media Composer | First, which included a large portion of Media Composer's functionality but its exporting workflows publishing finished videos directly to web services like YouTube.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] On March 29, 1999, Avid Technology, Inc. adjusted the amount originally allocated to IPR&D and restated its third-quarter 1998 consolidated financial statements accordingly, considering the SEC's views.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] In February 2018, Avid appointed Jeff Rosica as CEO, after terminating Louis Hernandez Jr, who was accused of workplace misconduct.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] In November 2023, Avid Technology was acquired by an affiliate of STG for $1.4 billion.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] This process delisted Avid from the public stock exchange, making it private.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] In April 2024, Avid appointed Wellford Dillard as CEO, succeeding Jeff Rosica.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] 1993: The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences awarded Avid Technology and all of the company's initial employees with a technical Emmy award for Outstanding Engineering Development for the Avid Media Composer video editing system.
[src:camera-monitor/avid-technology] 1999: At the 71st Academy Awards, Avid Technology Inc. was awarded an Oscar for the concept, system design and engineering of the Avid Film Composer for motion picture editing which was accepted by founder Bill Warner.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] An **electric battery** is a source of electric power consisting of one or more electrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] When a battery is supplying power, its positive terminal is the cathode and its negative terminal is the anode.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The terminal marked negative is the source of electrons.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] When a battery is connected to an external electric load, those negatively charged electrons flow through the circuit and reach the positive terminal, thus causing a redox reaction by attracting positively charged ions, or cations.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Thus, higher energy reactants are converted to lower energy products, and the free-energy difference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Historically the term "battery" specifically referred to a device composed of multiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a single cell.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Primary (single-use or "disposable") batteries are used once and discarded, as the electrode materials are irreversibly changed during discharge; a common example is the alkaline battery used for flashlights and a multitude of portable electronic devices.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Secondary (rechargeable) batteries can be discharged and recharged multiple times using an applied electric current; the original composition of the electrodes can be restored by reverse current.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Examples include the lead–acid automotive battery used in internal combustion engine vehicles, and lithium-ion batteries used for portable electronics and electric cars.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries come in many shapes and sizes, from miniature cells used to power hearing aids and wristwatches to, at the largest extreme, huge battery banks the size of rooms that provide standby or emergency power for telephone exchanges and computer data centers.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries have much lower specific energy (energy per unit mass) than common fuels such as gasoline.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In automobiles, this is somewhat offset by the higher efficiency of electric motors in converting electrical energy to mechanical work, compared to combustion engines.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Benjamin Franklin first used the term "battery" in 1749 when he was doing experiments with electricity using a set of linked Leyden jar capacitors.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Franklin grouped a number of the jars into what he described as a "battery", using the military term for weapons functioning together.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] By multiplying the number of holding vessels, a stronger charge could be stored, and more power would be available on discharge.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Italian physicist Alessandro Volta built and described the first electrochemical battery, the voltaic pile, in 1800.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] This was a stack of copper and zinc plates, separated by brine-soaked paper disks, that could produce a steady current for a considerable length of time.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Volta did not understand that the voltage was due to chemical reactions.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] He thought that his cells were an inexhaustible source of energy, and that the associated corrosion effects at the electrodes were a mere nuisance, rather than an unavoidable consequence of their operation, as Michael Faraday showed in 1834.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Although early batteries were of great value for experimental purposes, in practice their voltages fluctuated and they could not provide a large current for a sustained period.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The Daniell cell, invented in 1836 by British chemist John Frederic Daniell, was the first practical source of electricity, becoming an industry standard and seeing widespread adoption as a power source for electrical telegraph networks.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] It consisted of a copper pot filled with a copper sulfate solution, in which was immersed an unglazed earthenware container filled with sulfuric acid and a zinc electrode.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] These wet cells used liquid electrolytes, which were prone to leakage and spillage if not handled correctly.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Many used glass jars to hold their components, which made them fragile and potentially dangerous.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] These characteristics made wet cells unsuitable for portable appliances.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Near the end of the nineteenth century, the invention of dry cell batteries, which replaced the liquid electrolyte with a paste, made portable electrical devices practical.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries in vacuum tube devices historically used a wet cell for the "A" battery (to provide power to the filament) and a dry cell for the "B" battery (to provide the plate voltage).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Between 2010 and 2018, battery demand grew by 30% annually, reaching a total of 180 GWh in 2018.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Conservatively, the growth rate is expected to be maintained at an estimated 25%, culminating in demand reaching 2600 GWh in 2030.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In addition, cost reductions are expected to further increase the demand to as much as 3562 GWh.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Important reasons for this high rate of growth of the electric battery industry include the electrification of transport, and large-scale deployment in electricity grids, supported by decarbonization initiatives.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Distributed electric batteries, such as those used in battery electric vehicles (vehicle-to-grid) and in home energy storage with smart metering and that are connected to smart grids for demand response are active participants in smart power supply grids.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Secondary use of partially depleted batteries can add to the overall utility of electric batteries by reducing energy storage costs and emission impact due to longer service life.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In this use, vehicle electric batteries that have their battery capacity reduced to less than 80% (usually after 5–8 years of service) are repurposed for use in backup supplies or renewable energy storage systems.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage envisages the large-scale use of batteries to collect and store energy from the grid or a power plant and then discharge that energy at a later time to provide electricity or other grid services when needed.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage (either turnkey or distributed) are important components of smart power supply grids.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The advent of computational modeling has revolutionized battery materials design, enabling high-throughput screening and atomistic simulations that accelerate the discovery of novel electrolytes and electrodes, moving beyond traditional trial-and-error approaches.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In many cases, the electrical energy released is the difference in the cohesive or bond energies of the metals, oxides, or molecules undergoing the electrochemical reaction.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] For instance, energy can be stored in Zn or Li, which are high-energy metals because they are not stabilized by d-electron bonding, unlike transition metals.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries are designed so that the energetically favorable redox reaction can occur only when electrons move through the external part of the circuit.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A battery consists of some number of voltaic cells.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Each cell consists of two half-cells connected in series by a conductive electrolyte containing metal *cations*.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] One half-cell includes electrolyte and the negative electrode, the electrode to which anions (negatively charged ions) migrate; the other half-cell includes electrolyte and the positive electrode, to which cations (positively charged ions) migrate.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Cations are reduced (electrons are added) at the cathode, while metal atoms are oxidized (electrons are removed) at the anode.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Some cells use different electrolytes for each half-cell; then a separator is used to prevent mixing of the electrolytes while allowing ions to flow between half-cells to complete the electrical circuit.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Each half-cell has an electromotive force (*emf*, measured in volts) relative to a standard.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The net emf of the cell is the difference between the emfs of its half-cells.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Thus, if the electrodes have emfs ${\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}$ , then the net emf is ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}-{\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ ; in other words, the net emf is the difference between the reduction potentials of the half-reactions.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The electrical driving force or $\displaystyle {\Delta V_{\text{bat}}}$ across the terminals of a cell is known as the *terminal voltage (difference)* and is measured in volts.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The terminal voltage of a cell that is neither charging nor discharging is called the open-circuit voltage and equals the emf of the cell.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance, the terminal voltage of a cell that is discharging is smaller in magnitude than the open-circuit voltage and the terminal voltage of a cell that is charging exceeds the open-circuit voltage.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] An ideal cell has negligible internal resistance, so it would maintain a constant terminal voltage of ${\mathcal {E}}$ until exhausted, then dropping to zero.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] If such a cell maintained 1.5 volts and produced a charge of one coulomb then on complete discharge it would have performed 1.5 joules of work.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In actual cells, the internal resistance increases under discharge and the open-circuit voltage also decreases under discharge.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] If the voltage and resistance are plotted against time, the resulting graphs typically are a curve; the shape of the curve varies according to the chemistry and internal arrangement employed.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The voltage developed across a cell's terminals depends on the energy release of the chemical reactions of its electrodes and electrolyte.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Alkaline and zinc–carbon cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.5 volts; likewise NiCd and NiMH cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.2 volts.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The high electrochemical potential changes in the reactions of lithium compounds give lithium cells emfs of 3 volts or more.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Almost any liquid or moist object that has enough ions to be electrically conductive can serve as the electrolyte for a cell.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] As a novelty or science demonstration, it is possible to insert two electrodes made of different metals into a lemon, potato, etc. and generate small amounts of electricity.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A voltaic pile can be made from two coins (such as a nickel and a penny) and a piece of paper towel dipped in salt water.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Such a pile generates a very low voltage but, when many are stacked in series, they can replace normal batteries for a short time.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Some types of primary batteries used, for example, for telegraph circuits, were restored to operation by replacing the electrodes.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries are not indefinitely rechargeable due to dissipation of the active materials, loss of electrolyte and internal corrosion.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Primary batteries, or primary cells, can produce current immediately on assembly.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] These are most commonly used in portable devices that have low current drain, are used only intermittently, or are used well away from an alternative power source, such as in alarm and communication circuits where other electric power is only intermittently available.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Disposable primary cells cannot be reliably recharged, since the chemical reactions are not easily reversible and active materials may not return to their original forms.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Battery manufacturers recommend against attempting to recharge primary cells.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In general, these have higher energy densities than rechargeable batteries, but disposable batteries do not fare well under high-drain applications with loads under 75 ohms (75 Ω).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Common types of disposable batteries include zinc–carbon batteries and alkaline batteries.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries, also known as *secondary cells*, or *rechargeable batteries*, must be charged before first use; they are usually assembled with active materials in the discharged state.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Rechargeable batteries are (re)charged by applying electric current, which reverses the chemical reactions that occur during discharge/use.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Devices to supply the appropriate current are called chargers.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The oldest form of rechargeable battery is the lead–acid battery, which are widely used in automotive and boating applications.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] This technology contains liquid electrolyte in an unsealed container, requiring that the battery be kept upright and the area be well ventilated to ensure safe dispersal of the hydrogen gas it produces during overcharging.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The lead–acid battery is relatively heavy for the amount of electrical energy it can supply.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Its low manufacturing cost and its high surge current levels make it common where its capacity (over approximately 10 Ah) is more important than weight and handling issues.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A common application is the modern car battery, which can, in general, deliver a peak current of 450 amperes.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Many types of electrochemical cells have been produced, with varying chemical processes and designs, including galvanic cells, electrolytic cells, fuel cells, flow cells and voltaic piles.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A *wet cell* battery has a liquid electrolyte.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Other names are *flooded cell*, since the liquid covers all internal parts or *vented cell*, since gases produced during operation can escape to the air.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Wet cells were a precursor to dry cells and are commonly used as a learning tool for electrochemistry.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] They can be built with common laboratory supplies, such as beakers, for demonstrations of how electrochemical cells work.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A particular type of wet cell known as a concentration cell is important in understanding corrosion.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Wet cells may be primary cells (non-rechargeable) or secondary cells (rechargeable).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Originally, all practical primary batteries, such as the Daniell cell, were built as open-top glass jar wet cells.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Other primary wet cells are the Leclanche cell, Grove cell, Bunsen cell, Chromic acid cell, Clark cell, and Weston cell.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The Leclanche cell chemistry was adapted to the first dry cells.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Wet cells are still used in automobile batteries and in industry for standby power for switchgear, telecommunication or large uninterruptible power supplies, but in many places batteries with gel cells have been used instead.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] These applications commonly use lead–acid or nickel–cadmium cells.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Molten salt batteries are primary or secondary batteries that use a molten salt as electrolyte.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] They operate at high temperatures and must be well insulated to retain heat.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A *dry cell* uses a paste electrolyte, with only enough moisture to allow current to flow.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Unlike a wet cell, a dry cell can operate in any orientation without spilling, as it contains no free liquid, making it suitable for portable equipment.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] By comparison, the first wet cells were typically fragile glass containers with lead rods hanging from the open top and needed careful handling to avoid spillage.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries did not achieve the safety and portability of the dry cell until the development of the gel battery.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A common dry cell is the zinc–carbon battery, sometimes called the dry Leclanché cell, with a nominal voltage of 1.5 volts, the same as the alkaline battery (since both use the same zinc–manganese dioxide combination).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A standard dry cell comprises a zinc anode, usually in the form of a cylindrical pot, with a carbon cathode in the form of a central rod.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The electrolyte is ammonium chloride in the form of a paste next to the zinc anode.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The remaining space between the electrolyte and carbon cathode is taken up by a second paste consisting of ammonium chloride and manganese dioxide, the latter acting as a depolariser.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In some designs, the ammonium chloride is replaced by zinc chloride.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A reserve battery can be stored unassembled (unactivated and supplying no power) for a long period (perhaps years).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] When the battery is needed, then it is assembled (e.g., by adding electrolyte); once assembled, the battery is charged and ready to work.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] For example, a battery for an electronic artillery fuze might be activated by the impact of firing a gun.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The acceleration breaks a capsule of electrolyte that activates the battery and powers the fuze's circuits.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Reserve batteries are usually designed for a short service life (seconds or minutes) after long storage (years).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A water-activated battery for oceanographic instruments or military applications becomes activated on immersion in water.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The solid-state battery is also said to have "three times the energy density", increasing its useful life in electric vehicles, for example.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] It should also be more ecologically sound since the technology uses less expensive, earth-friendly materials such as sodium extracted from seawater.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Sony has developed a biological battery that generates electricity from sugar in a way that is similar to the processes observed in living organisms.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The battery generates electricity through the use of enzymes that break down carbohydrates.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The sealed valve regulated lead–acid battery (VRLA battery) is popular in the automotive industry as a replacement for the lead–acid wet cell.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The VRLA battery uses an immobilized sulfuric acid electrolyte, reducing the chance of leakage and extending shelf life.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] VRLA batteries immobilize the electrolyte.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Other portable rechargeable batteries include several sealed "dry cell" types, that are useful in applications such as mobile phones and laptop computers.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Cells of this type (in order of increasing power density and cost) include nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–zinc (NiZn), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), and lithium-ion (Li-ion) cells.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Li-ion has by far the highest share of the dry cell rechargeable market.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] NiMH has replaced NiCd in most applications due to its higher capacity, but NiCd remains in use in power tools, two-way radios, and medical equipment.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Low self-discharge (LSD) allows secondary cells to be charged prior to shipping.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Lithium–sulfur batteries were used on the longest and highest solar-powered flight.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries of all types are manufactured in consumer and industrial grades.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Standard-format batteries are inserted into battery holder in the device that uses them.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] When a device does not uses standard-format batteries, they are typically combined into a custom battery pack which holds multiple batteries in addition to features such as a battery management system and battery isolator which ensure that the batteries within are charged and discharged evenly.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Primary batteries readily available to consumers range from tiny button cells used for electric watches, to the No.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] 6 cell used for signal circuits or other long duration applications.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Secondary cells are made in very large sizes; very large batteries can power a submarine or stabilize an electrical grid and help level out peak loads.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] As of 2017, the world's largest battery was built in South Australia by Tesla.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A battery in Hebei Province, China, which can store 36 MWh of electricity was built in 2013 at a cost of $500 million.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Another large battery, composed of Ni–Cd cells, was in Fairbanks, Alaska.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] It covered 2,000 square metres (22,000 sq ft)—bigger than a football pitch—and weighed 1,300 tonnes.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] It was manufactured by ABB to provide backup power in the event of a blackout.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The battery can provide 40 MW of power for up to seven minutes.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Sodium–sulfur batteries have been used to store wind power.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A 4.4 MWh battery system that can deliver 11 MW for 25 minutes stabilizes the output of the Auwahi wind farm in Hawaii.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Many important cell properties, such as voltage, energy density, flammability, available cell constructions, operating temperature range and shelf life, are dictated by battery chemistry.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A battery's characteristics may vary over load cycle, over charge cycle, and over lifetime due to many factors including internal chemistry, current drain, and temperature.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] At low temperatures, a battery cannot deliver as much power.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] As such, in cold climates, some car owners install battery warmers, which are small electric heating pads that keep the car battery warm.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A battery's *capacity* is the amount of electric charge it can deliver at a voltage that does not drop below the specified terminal voltage.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The more electrode material contained in the cell the greater its capacity.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A small cell has less capacity than a larger cell with the same chemistry, although they develop the same open-circuit voltage.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Capacity is usually stated in ampere-hours (A·h) (mAh for small batteries).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The rated capacity of a battery is usually expressed as the product of 20 hours multiplied by the current that a new battery can consistently supply for 20 hours at 20 °C (68 °F), while remaining above a specified terminal voltage per cell.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 100 A·h can deliver 5 A over a 20-hour period at room temperature.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The fraction of the stored charge that a battery can deliver depends on multiple factors, including battery chemistry, the rate at which the charge is delivered (current), the required terminal voltage, the storage period, ambient temperature and other factors.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The higher the discharge rate, the lower the capacity.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] is the capacity when discharged at a rate of 1 amp.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] is the amount of time (in hours) that a battery can sustain.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Charged batteries (rechargeable or disposable) lose charge by internal self-discharge over time although not discharged, due to the presence of generally irreversible *side reactions* that consume charge carriers without producing current.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The rate of self-discharge depends upon battery chemistry and construction, typically from months to years for significant loss.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] When batteries are recharged, additional side reactions reduce capacity for subsequent discharges.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] After enough recharges, in essence all capacity is lost and the battery stops producing power.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Internal energy losses and limitations on the rate that ions pass through the electrolyte cause battery efficiency to vary.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Above a minimum threshold, discharging at a low rate delivers more of the battery's capacity than at a higher rate.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Installing batteries with varying A·h ratings changes operating time, but not device operation unless load limits are exceeded.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] High-drain loads such as digital cameras can reduce total capacity of rechargeable or disposable batteries.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 2 A·h for a 10- or 20-hour discharge would not sustain a current of 1 A for a full two hours as its stated capacity suggests.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The C-rate is a measure of the rate at which a battery is being charged or discharged.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] It is defined as the current through the battery divided by the theoretical current draw under which the battery would deliver its nominal rated capacity in one hour.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance loss and the chemical processes inside the cells, a battery rarely delivers nameplate rated capacity in only one hour.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Typically, maximum capacity is found at a low C-rate, and charging or discharging at a higher C-rate reduces the usable life and capacity of a battery.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Manufacturers often publish datasheets with graphs showing capacity versus C-rate curves.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] C-rate is also used as a rating on batteries to indicate the maximum current that a battery can safely deliver in a circuit.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Standards for rechargeable batteries generally rate the capacity and charge cycles over a 4-hour (0.25C), 8 hour (0.125C) or longer discharge time.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Types intended for special purposes, such as in a computer uninterruptible power supply, may be rated by manufacturers for discharge periods much less than one hour (1C) but may suffer from limited cycle life.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In 2009 experimental lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4) battery technology provided the fastest charging and energy delivery, discharging all its energy into a load in 10 to 20 seconds.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In 2024 a prototype battery for electric cars that could charge from 10% to 80% in five minutes was demonstrated, and a Chinese company claimed that car batteries it had introduced charged 10% to 80% in 10.5 minutes—the fastest batteries available—compared to Tesla's 15 minutes to half-charge.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Battery life (or lifetime) has two meanings for rechargeable batteries but only one for non-chargeable batteries.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] It can be used to describe the length of time a device can run on a fully charged battery—this is also unambiguously termed "endurance".
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] For a rechargeable battery it may also be used for the number of charge/discharge cycles possible before the cells fail to operate satisfactorily—this is also termed "lifespan".
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The term *shelf life* is used to describe how long a battery will retain its performance between manufacture and use.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Available capacity of all batteries drops with decreasing temperature.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In contrast to most of today's batteries, the Zamboni pile, invented in 1812, offers a very long service life without refurbishment or recharge, although it can supply very little current (nanoamps).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The Oxford Electric Bell has been ringing almost continuously since 1840 on its original pair of batteries, thought to be Zamboni piles.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Disposable batteries typically lose 8–20% of their original charge per year when stored at room temperature (20–30 °C).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] This is known as the "self-discharge" rate, and is due to non-current-producing "side" chemical reactions that occur within the cell even when no load is applied.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The rate of side reactions is reduced for batteries stored at lower temperatures, although some can be damaged by freezing and storing in a fridge will not meaningfully prolong shelf life and risks damaging condensation.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Old rechargeable batteries self-discharge more rapidly than disposable alkaline batteries, especially nickel-based batteries; a freshly charged nickel cadmium (NiCd) battery loses 10% of its charge in the first 24 hours, and thereafter discharges at a rate of about 10% a month.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] However, newer low self-discharge nickel–metal hydride (NiMH) batteries and modern lithium designs display a lower self-discharge rate (but still higher than for primary batteries).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The active material on the battery plates changes chemical composition on each charge and discharge cycle; active material may be lost due to physical changes of volume, further limiting the number of times the battery can be recharged.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Most nickel-based batteries are partially discharged when purchased, and must be charged before first use.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Newer NiMH batteries are ready to be used when purchased, and have only 15% discharge in a year.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Some deterioration occurs on each charge–discharge cycle.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Degradation usually occurs because electrolyte migrates away from the electrodes or because active material detaches from the electrodes.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Low-capacity NiMH batteries (1,700–2,000 mA·h) can be charged some 1,000 times, whereas high-capacity NiMH batteries (above 2,500 mA·h) last about 500 cycles.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] NiCd batteries tend to be rated for 1,000 cycles before their internal resistance permanently increases beyond usable values.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Fast charging increases component changes, shortening battery lifespan.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] If a charger cannot detect when the battery is fully charged then overcharging is likely, damaging it.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] NiCd cells, if used in a particular repetitive manner, may show a decrease in capacity called "memory effect".
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The effect can be avoided with simple practices.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] NiMH cells, although similar in chemistry, suffer less from memory effect.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Automotive lead–acid rechargeable batteries must endure stress due to vibration, shock, and temperature range.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Because of these stresses and sulfation of their lead plates, few automotive batteries last beyond six years of regular use.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Automotive starting (SLI: *Starting, Lighting, Ignition*) batteries have many thin plates to maximize current.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In general, the thicker the plates the longer the life.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] They are typically discharged only slightly before recharge.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] "Deep-cycle" lead–acid batteries such as those used in electric golf carts have much thicker plates to extend longevity.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The main benefit of the lead–acid battery is its low cost; its main drawbacks are large size and weight for a given capacity and voltage.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries should never be discharged to below 20% of their capacity, because internal resistance will cause heat and damage when they are recharged.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Deep-cycle lead–acid systems often use a low-charge warning light or a low-charge power cut-off switch to prevent the type of damage that will shorten the battery's life.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Battery life can be extended by storing the batteries at a low temperature, as in a refrigerator or freezer, which slows the side reactions.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Such storage can extend the life of alkaline batteries by about 5%; rechargeable batteries can hold their charge much longer, depending upon type.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] To reach their maximum voltage, batteries must be returned to room temperature; discharging an alkaline battery at 250 mA at 0 °C is only half as efficient as at 20 °C.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Alkaline battery manufacturers such as Duracell do not recommend refrigerating batteries.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] A battery explosion is generally caused by misuse or malfunction, such as attempting to recharge a primary (non-rechargeable) battery, or a short circuit.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] When a battery is recharged at an excessive rate, an explosive gas mixture of hydrogen and oxygen may be produced faster than it can escape from within the battery (e.g. through a built-in vent), leading to pressure build-up and eventual bursting of the battery case.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In extreme cases, battery chemicals may spray violently from the casing and cause injury.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] An expert summary of the problem indicates that this type uses "liquid electrolytes to transport lithium ions between the anode and the cathode.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] If a battery cell is charged too quickly, it can cause a short circuit, leading to explosions and fires".
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Car batteries are most likely to explode when a short circuit generates very large currents.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Such batteries produce hydrogen, which is very explosive, when they are overcharged (because of electrolysis of the water in the electrolyte).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] During normal use, the amount of overcharging is usually very small and generates little hydrogen, which dissipates quickly.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] However, when "jump starting" a car, the high current can cause the rapid release of large volumes of hydrogen, which can be ignited explosively by a nearby spark, e.g. when disconnecting a jumper cable.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Overcharging (attempting to charge a battery beyond its electrical capacity) can also lead to a battery explosion, in addition to leakage or irreversible damage.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] It may also cause damage to the charger or device in which the overcharged battery is later used.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Disposing of a battery via incineration may cause an explosion as steam builds up within the sealed case.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Many battery chemicals are corrosive, poisonous or both.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] If leakage occurs, either spontaneously or through accident, the chemicals released may be dangerous.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] For example, disposable batteries often use a zinc "can" both as a reactant and as the container to hold the other reagents.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] If this kind of battery is over-discharged, the reagents can emerge through the cardboard and plastic that form the remainder of the container.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The active chemical leakage can then damage or disable the equipment that the batteries power.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] For this reason, many electronic device manufacturers recommend removing the batteries from devices that will not be used for extended periods of time.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Many types of batteries employ toxic materials such as lead, mercury, and cadmium as an electrode or electrolyte.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] When each battery reaches end of life it must be disposed of to prevent environmental damage.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries are one form of electronic waste (e-waste).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] E-waste recycling services recover toxic substances, which can then be used for new batteries.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Of the nearly three billion batteries purchased annually in the United States, about 179,000 tons end up in landfills across the country.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries may be harmful or fatal if swallowed.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Small button cells can be swallowed, in particular by young children.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] While in the digestive tract, the battery's electrical discharge may lead to tissue damage; such damage is occasionally serious and can lead to death.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Ingested disk batteries do not usually cause problems unless they become lodged in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The most common place for disk batteries to become lodged is the esophagus, resulting in clinical sequelae.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Batteries that successfully traverse the esophagus are unlikely to lodge elsewhere.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The likelihood that a disk battery will lodge in the esophagus is a function of the patient's age and the size of the battery.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Older children do not have problems with batteries smaller than 21–23 mm.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Liquefaction necrosis may occur because sodium hydroxide is generated by the current produced by the battery (usually at the anode).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Perforation has occurred as rapidly as 6 hours after ingestion.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Some manufacturers add a bittering agent to their batteries to discourage swallowing.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] Legislation around electric batteries includes such topics as safe disposal and recycling.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In response to reported accidents and failures, occasionally ignition or explosion, recalls of devices using lithium-ion batteries have become more common in recent years.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In the United States, the Mercury-Containing and Rechargeable Battery Management Act of 1996 banned the sale of mercury-containing batteries, enacted uniform labeling requirements for rechargeable batteries and required that rechargeable batteries be easily removable.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] California and New York City prohibit the disposal of rechargeable batteries in solid waste.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The rechargeable battery industry operates nationwide recycling programs in the United States and Canada, with dropoff points at local retailers.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] The Battery Directive of the European Union has similar requirements, in addition to requiring increased recycling of batteries and promoting research on improved battery recycling methods.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] In accordance with this directive all batteries to be sold within the EU must be marked with the "collection symbol" (a crossed-out wheeled bin).
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] This must cover at least 3% of the surface of prismatic batteries and 1.5% of the surface of cylindrical batteries.
[src:camera-monitor/battery-electricity] On 9 December 2022, the European Parliament reached an agreement to force, from 2026, manufacturers to design all electrical appliances sold in the EU (and not used predominantly in wet conditions) so that consumers can easily remove and replace batteries themselves.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] A **camera monitor** (or **external monitor**) is a monitor that attaches externally to a digital camera to aid with photography and cinematography.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] Camera monitors typically have larger displays than the built-in monitors on consumer cameras, and are also usually brighter and able to reproduce color better.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] Consumer friendly units use HDMI for connecting to the camera, while higher end camera monitors may also offer SDI connections.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] While some are powered by a single battery, others can be powered by two batteries and offer a hot swapping capability.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] It's not uncommon for an AC adapter to be available as well for indoor photography or filming.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] In addition to providing a larger display, many camera monitors provide additional tools to assist camera operators.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] Such tools include framing guides, focus peaking, zebra stripes, waveform monitors (oftentimes as an "RGB parade"), vectorscopes and false color to highlight areas of the image critical to the operator.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] Most typically provide the ability to apply a LUT to the video in real-time allowing filmmakers to view their footage with their color grading already applied.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] Some camera monitors also offer a recording function.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] These recorders typically encode footage in a higher quality (using CODECs such as Apple ProRes or Avid Technology's DNxHR codec) and to larger storage mediums than many consumer cameras provide internally.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] Additionally, many cameras output higher quality video (with less or no chroma subsampling and potentially a higher color depth) through their external connections than they can record internally.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] For example, some cameras output 10-bit color with 4:2:2 chroma subsampling through their HDMI connections, while only recording 8-bit color with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling internally.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] Recorder monitors are also used in conjunction with PTZ cameras to allow recording and editing on the fly.
[src:camera-monitor/camera-monitor] This has the twin benefit of avoiding the PTZ camera getting too hot as well as allowing editing to take place in real time with the use of LUTs etc., thus saving time and money.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] It is used in many video and still image encoding schemes – both analog and digital – including in JPEG encoding.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Digital signals are often compressed to reduce file size and save transmission time.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Since the human visual system is much more sensitive to variations in brightness than color, a video system can be optimized by devoting more bandwidth to the luma component (usually denoted Y'), than to the color difference components **Cb** and **Cr**.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In compressed images, for example, the 4:2:2 Y'CbCr scheme requires two-thirds the bandwidth of non-subsampled "4:4:4" R'G'B'.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This reduction results in almost no visual difference as perceived by the viewer.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The human vision system processes color information (hue and colorfulness) at about a third of the resolution of luminance (lightness/darkness information in an image).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Therefore it is possible to sample color information at a lower resolution while maintaining good image quality.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This is achieved by encoding RGB image data into a composite black and white image, with separated color difference data (chroma).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] For example with $Y'C_{b}C_{r}$ , gamma encoded $R'G'B'$ components are weighted and then summed together to create the luma $Y'$ component.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The color difference components are created by subtracting two of the weighted $R'G'B'$ components from the third.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] A variety of filtering methods can be used to limit the resolution.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Gamma encoded luma $Y'$ should not be confused with linear luminance Y .
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The presence of gamma encoding is denoted with the prime symbol ' .
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Gamma-correcting electro-optical transfer functions (EOTF) are used due to the nonlinear response of human vision.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The use of gamma improves perceived signal-to-noise in analogue systems, and allows for more efficient data encoding in digital systems.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This encoding uses more levels for darker colors than for lighter ones, accommodating human vision sensitivity.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The subsampling scheme is commonly expressed as a three-part ratio *J*:*a*:*b* (e.g.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:2) or four parts, if alpha channel is present (e.g.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:2:4), that describe the number of luminance and chrominance samples in a conceptual region that is *J* pixels wide and 2 pixels high.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This notation is not valid for all combinations and has exceptions, e.g.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 4:1:0 (where the height of the region is not 2 pixels, but 4 pixels, so if 8 bits per component are used, the media would be 9 bits per pixel) and 4:2:1.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The mapping examples given are only theoretical and for illustration.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Also the diagram does not indicate any chroma filtering, which should be applied to avoid aliasing.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] To calculate required bandwidth factor relative to 4:4:4 (or 4:4:4:4), one needs to sum all the factors and divide the result by 12 (or 16, if alpha is present).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Each of the three Y'CbCr components has the same sample rate, thus there is no chroma subsampling.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This scheme is sometimes used in high-end film scanners and cinematic post-production.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] "4:4:4" may instead be wrongly referring to R'G'B' color space, which implicitly also does not have any chroma subsampling (except in JPEG R'G'B' can be subsampled).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Formats such as HDCAM SR can record 4:4:4 R'G'B' over dual-link HD-SDI.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The two chroma components are sampled at half the horizontal sample rate of luma: the horizontal chroma resolution is halved.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This reduces the bandwidth of an uncompressed video signal by one-third, which means for 8 bit per component without alpha (24 bit per pixel) only 16 bits are enough, as in NV16.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In 4:1:1 chroma subsampling, the horizontal color resolution is quartered, and the bandwidth is halved compared to no chroma subsampling.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Initially, 4:1:1 chroma subsampling of the DV format was not considered to be broadcast quality and was only acceptable for low-end and consumer applications.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] However, DV-based formats (some of which use 4:1:1 chroma subsampling) have been used professionally in electronic news gathering and in playout servers.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] DV has also been sporadically used in feature films and in digital cinematography.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] However, in most equipment, especially cheap TV sets and VHS/Betamax VCRs, the chroma channels have only the 0.5 MHz bandwidth for both **Cr** and **Cb** (or equivalently for I/Q).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Thus the DV system actually provides a superior color bandwidth compared to the best composite analog specifications for NTSC, despite having only 1/4 of the chroma bandwidth of a "full" digital signal.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In 4:2:0, the horizontal sampling is doubled compared to 4:1:1, but as the **Cb** and **Cr** channels are only sampled on each alternate line in this scheme, the vertical resolution is halved.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This fits reasonably well with the PAL color encoding system, since this has only half the vertical chrominance resolution of NTSC.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] It would also fit extremely well with the SECAM color encoding system, since like that format, 4:2:0 only stores and transmits one color channel per line (the other channel being recovered from the previous line).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] However, little equipment has actually been produced that outputs a SECAM analogue video signal.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In general, SECAM territories either have to use a PAL-capable display or a transcoder to convert the PAL signal to SECAM for display.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] There are four main variants of 4:2:0 schemes, having different horizontal and vertical sampling relative to the 2×2 "square" of the original input size.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] With interlaced material, 4:2:0 chroma subsampling can result in motion artifacts if it is implemented the same way as for progressive material.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The luma samples are derived from separate time intervals, while the chroma samples would be derived from both time intervals.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] It is this difference that can result in motion artifacts.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The MPEG-2 standard allows for an alternate interlaced sampling scheme, where 4:2:0 is applied to each field (not both fields at once).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This solves the problem of motion artifacts, reduces the vertical chroma resolution by half, and can introduce comb-like artifacts in the image.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The moving text has some motion blur applied to it.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **progressive** sampling applied to moving *interlaced* material.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The chroma leads and trails the moving text.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **interlaced** sampling applied to moving *interlaced* material.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In the 4:2:0 interlaced scheme, however, vertical resolution of the chroma is roughly halved, since the chroma samples effectively describe an area 2 samples wide by 4 samples tall instead of 2×2.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] As well, the spatial displacement between both fields can result in the appearance of comb-like chroma artifacts.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **progressive** sampling applied to a still image.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **interlaced** sampling applied to a still image.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] If the interlaced material is to be de-interlaced, the comb-like chroma artifacts (from 4:2:0 interlaced sampling) can be removed by blurring the chroma vertically.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This ratio is possible, and some codecs support it, but it is not widely used.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This ratio uses half of the vertical and one-fourth the horizontal color resolutions, with only one-eighth of the bandwidth of the maximum color resolutions used.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Uncompressed video in this format with 8-bit quantization uses 10 bytes for every macropixel (which is 4×2 pixels) or 10 bit for every pixel.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] It has the equivalent chrominance bandwidth of a PAL-I or PAL-M signal decoded with a delay line decoder, and still very much superior to NTSC.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Used by Sony in their HDCAM High Definition recorders (not HDCAM SR).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In the horizontal dimension, luma is sampled horizontally at three quarters of the full HD sampling rate – 1440 samples per row instead of 1920.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Chroma is sampled at 480 samples per row, a third of the luma sampling rate.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In the vertical dimension, both luma and chroma are sampled at the full HD sampling rate (1080 samples vertically).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] A number of legacy schemes allow different subsampling factors in Cb and Cr, similar to how a different amount of bandwidth is allocated to the two chroma values in broadcast systems such as CCIR System M.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] These schemes are not expressible in *J:a:b* notation.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Instead, they adopt a *Y:Cb:Cr* notation, with each part describing the amount of resolution for the corresponding component.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] It is unspecified whether the resolution reduction happens in the horizontal or vertical direction.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Original image without color subsampling.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Note the bleeding in lightness near the borders.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Chroma subsampling suffers from two main types of artifacts, causing degradation more noticeable than intended where colors change abruptly.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Gamma-corrected signals like Y'CbCr have an issue where chroma errors "bleed" into luma.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In those signals, a low chroma actually makes a color appear less bright than one with equivalent luma.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] As a result, when a saturated color blends with an unsaturated or complementary color, a loss of luminance occurs at the border.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This can be seen in the example between magenta and green.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This issue persists in HDR video where gamma is generalized into a transfer function "EOTF".
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] A steeper EOTF shows a stronger luminance loss.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] 2020 defines a "constant luminance" Yc'CbcCrc, which is calculated from linear RGB components and then gamma-encoded.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] This version does not suffer from the luminance loss by design.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Another artifact that can occur with chroma subsampling is that out-of-gamut colors can occur upon chroma reconstruction.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Suppose the image consisted of alternating 1-pixel red and black lines and the subsampling omitted the chroma for the black pixels.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Chroma from the red pixels will be reconstructed onto the black pixels, causing the new pixels to have positive red and *negative* green and blue values.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] As displays cannot output negative light (negative light does not exist), these negative values will effectively be clipped, and the resulting luma value will be too high.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Other sub-sampling filters (especially the averaging "box") have a similar issue that is harder to make a simple example out of.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Similar artifacts arise in the less artificial example of gradation near a fairly sharp red/black boundary.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] It is possible for the decoder to deal with out-of-gamut colors by considering how much chroma a given luma value can hold and distribute it into the 4:4:4 intermediate accordingly, termed "in-range chroma reconstruction" by Glenn Chan.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The "proportion" method is in spirit similar to Kornelski's luma-weighted average, while the "spill" method resembles error diffusion.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Improving chroma reconstruction remains an active field of research.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The term Y'UV refers to an analog TV encoding scheme (ITU-R Rec.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] BT.470) while Y'CbCr refers to a digital encoding scheme.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] One difference between the two is that the scale factors on the chroma components (U, V, Cb, and Cr) are different.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] However, the term YUV is often used erroneously to refer to Y'CbCr encoding.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Hence, expressions like "4:2:2 YUV" always refer to 4:2:2 Y'CbCr, since there simply is no such thing as 4:x:x in analog encoding (such as YUV).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Pixel formats used in Y'CbCr can be referred to as YUV too, for example yuv420p, yuvj420p and many others.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In a similar vein, the term luminance and the symbol Y are often used erroneously to refer to luma, which is denoted with the symbol Y'.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The *luma* (Y') of video engineering deviates from the *luminance* (Y) of color science (as defined by CIE).
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Luma is formed as the weighted sum of *gamma-corrected* (tristimulus) RGB components.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Luminance is formed as a weighed sum of *linear* (tristimulus) RGB components.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In practice, the CIE symbol Y is often incorrectly used to denote luma.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In 1993, SMPTE adopted Engineering Guideline EG 28, clarifying the two terms.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The prime symbol ' is used to indicate gamma correction.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Similarly, the chroma of video engineering differs from the chrominance of color science.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] The chroma of video engineering is formed from weighted tristimulus components (gamma corrected, OETF), not linear components.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] In video engineering practice, the terms *chroma*, *chrominance*, and *saturation* are often used interchangeably to refer to chroma, but it is not a good practice, as ITU-T Rec H.273 says.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Chroma subsampling was developed in the 1950s by Alda Bedford for the development of color television by RCA, which developed into the NTSC standard; luma–chroma separation was developed earlier, in 1938 by Georges Valensi.
[src:camera-monitor/chroma-subsampling] Through studies, he showed that the human eye has high resolution only for black and white, somewhat less for "mid-range" colors like yellows and greens, and much less for colors on the end of the spectrum, reds and blues.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] A **codec** is a computer hardware or software component that encodes or decodes a data stream or signal.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] *Codec* is a portmanteau of **coder/decoder**.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] In electronic communications, an **endec** is a device that acts as both an encoder and a decoder on a signal or data stream, and hence is a type of codec.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] *Endec* is a portmanteau of **encoder/decoder**.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] A coder or encoder encodes a data stream or a signal for transmission or storage, possibly in encrypted form, and the decoder function reverses the encoding for playback or editing.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Codecs are used in videoconferencing, streaming media, and video editing applications.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Originally, in the mid-20th century, a codec was a hardware device that coded analog signals into digital form using pulse-code modulation (PCM).
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Later, the term was also applied to software for converting between digital signal formats, including companding functions.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] An audio codec converts analog audio signals into digital signals for transmission or encodes them for storage.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] A receiving device converts the digital signals back to analog form using an audio decoder for playback.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] An example of this is the codecs used in the sound cards of personal computers.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] A video codec accomplishes the same task for video signals.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] When implementing the Infrared Data Association (IrDA) protocol, an endec may be used between the UART and the optoelectronic systems.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Examples of hardware codecs include Intel QSV and Azalia Audio; examples of software codecs include FFmpeg (and its Libavcodec).
[src:camera-monitor/codec] In addition to encoding a signal, a codec may also compress the data to reduce transmission bandwidth or storage space.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Compression codecs are classified primarily into lossy codecs and lossless codecs.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Lossless codecs are often used for archiving data in compressed form while retaining all information present in the original stream.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] If preserving the original quality of the stream is more important than eliminating the correspondingly larger data sizes, lossless codecs are preferred.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Using more than one codec or encoding scheme successively can also degrade quality significantly.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] The decreasing cost of storage capacity and network bandwidth has a tendency to reduce the need for lossy codecs for some media.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] They reduce quality in order to maximize compression.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Often, this type of compression is virtually indistinguishable from the original uncompressed sound or images, depending on the codec and the settings used.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] The most widely used lossy data compression technique in digital media is based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT), used in compression standards such as JPEG images, H.26x and MPEG video, and MP3 and AAC audio.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Smaller data sets ease the strain on relatively expensive storage sub-systems such as non-volatile memory and hard disk, as well as write-once-read-many formats such as CD-ROM, DVD, and Blu-ray Disc.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Lower data rates also reduce cost and improve performance when the data is transmitted, e.g., over the internet.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Two principal techniques are used in codecs, pulse-code modulation and delta modulation.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Codecs are often designed to emphasize certain aspects of the media to be encoded.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] For example, a digital video (using a DV codec) of a sports event needs to encode motion well but not necessarily exact colors, while a video of an art exhibit needs to encode color and surface texture well.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Audio codecs for cell phones need to have very low latency between source encoding and playback.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] In contrast, audio codecs for recording or broadcasting can use high-latency audio compression techniques to achieve higher fidelity at a lower bit rate.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] There are thousands of audio and video codecs, ranging in cost from free to hundreds of dollars or more.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] This variety of codecs can create compatibility and obsolescence issues.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] The impact is lessened for older formats, for which free or nearly-free codecs have existed for a long time.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] The older formats are often ill-suited to modern applications, however, such as playback on small portable devices.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] For example, raw uncompressed PCM audio (44.1 kHz, 16-bit stereo, as represented on an audio CD or in a .wav or .aiff file) has long been a standard across multiple platforms, but its transmission over networks is slow and expensive compared with more modern compressed formats, such as Opus and MP3.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Many multimedia data streams contain both audio and video, and often some metadata that permits synchronization of audio and video.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Each of these three streams may be handled by different programs, processes, or hardware, but for the multimedia data streams to be useful in stored or transmitted form, they must be encapsulated together in a container format.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Lower bitrate codecs allow more users, but they also have more distortion.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Beyond the initial increase in distortion, lower bit rate codecs also achieve their lower bit rates by using more complex algorithms that make certain assumptions, such as those about the media and the packet loss rate.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Other codecs may not make those same assumptions.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] When a user with a low bitrate codec talks to a user with another codec, additional distortion is introduced by each transcoding.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Audio Video Interleave (AVI) is sometimes erroneously described as a codec, but AVI is actually a container format, while a codec is a software or hardware tool that encodes or decodes audio or video into or from some audio or video format.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] Audio and video encoded with many codecs might be put into an AVI container, although AVI is not an ISO standard.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] There are also other well-known container formats, such as Ogg, ASF, QuickTime, RealMedia, Matroska, and DivX Media Format.
[src:camera-monitor/codec] MPEG transport stream, MPEG program stream, MP4, and ISO base media file format are examples of container formats that are ISO standardized.
